<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-913-366  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 913 366.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Educational Technology  Nov 1989 v29 n11 p18(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Some learning and instructional theory considerations for thedevelopment of computer related instructional materials.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Smith, Peter E.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Educational materials should be developed from a sound theoreticalbase.andP;  Computer-assisted instruction (CAI) has historically beeninfluenced by behaviorism, but now cognitive psychological theoryis also becoming a basis for CAI.andP;  Additionally, such theoreticalpositions as &quot;neobehaviorism,&quot; or imitation-modeling, informationprocessing, and learning styles are useful in developing CAImaterials.andP;  For each of these theoretical approaches, fiveguidelines for CAI developers are presented.andP;  Additionally,superordinate guidelines addressing such issues as feedback andreinforcement, practice, and guidance are also given.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Computer-Assisted InstructionSystem DevelopmentGuidelinesTheoryEducation.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>